Second option (to preserve void return type) will be to treat *nums* array as resulting array (newArr). It will keep return type void and updates will be &quot;visible&quot; from main method

**Explanation:**
In Java, when an object reference (in this case array of ints) is passed to a method, a copy of the reference is created and passed to the method. This means that the method receives a new reference that points to the same object as the original reference, but it is not the same reference.

To understand this, consider the following example:
```java
public class Example {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] arr = {1, 2, 3};
        changeArr(arr);
        System.out.println(Arrays.toString(arr));
    }
    
    public static void changeArr(int[] arr) {
        arr[0] = 0;
        arr = new int[] {4, 5, 6};
    }
}
```

In this example, an array arr is created and initialized with {1, 2, 3}. The changeArr method is then called, passing in a reference to arr.

Inside the changeArr method, the first element of arr is changed to 0, which modifies the original array. However, a new array {4, 5, 6} is created and the arr reference is updated to point to this new array.

When the method returns, the original reference arr still points to the modified array {0, 2, 3}, not to the new array {4, 5, 6}. This demonstrates that the reference passed to the method is different from the original reference, and that changes made to the object referred to by the reference are visible outside the method, but changes to the reference itself are not.

