To be able to use a custom class in some Gradle build, you’ll have to build that class in a different build first. In your `buildSrc` build, you’re trying to build the class in the same build in which you’re trying to use it – which isn’t possible.

After having built the class, you’ll want to get it into the second build. For that you’ll have to get it on the build script classpath of that second build. This is usually done via a custom Gradle plugin which contains or depends on the class.

### Sample Setup

Here’s a sample setup for your use case (tested with Gradle 8.0.2):

```lang-none
├── enumProvidingProj
│&#160;&#160; ├── build.gradle
│&#160;&#160; ├── settings.gradle
│&#160;&#160; └── src
│&#160;&#160;     └── main
│&#160;&#160;         ├── groovy
│&#160;&#160;         │&#160;&#160; └── my-enum-convention.gradle
│&#160;&#160;         └── java
│&#160;&#160;             └── SomeEnum.java
└── enumUsingProj
 &#160;&#160; ├── build.gradle
 &#160;&#160; └── settings.gradle
```

The `enumProvidingProj` builds the `SomeEnum` class and makes it available via a [precompiled script plugin](https://docs.gradle.org/8.0.2/userguide/custom_plugins.html#sec:precompiled_plugins). The `enumUsingProj` then uses the class after it has applied the plugin.  The `enumUsingProj` is hence equivalent to your `buildSrc` build; you can use it as an included build, for example.

Here are the contents of the listed sample files:

#### `enumProvidingProj/build.gradle`

```lang-groovy
plugins {
    id &#39;groovy-gradle-plugin&#39;
    id &#39;java&#39;
}
```

#### `enumProvidingProj/settings.gradle`

```lang-groovy
// empty file
```

#### `enumProvidingProj/src/main/groovy/my-enum-convention.gradle`

```lang-groovy
// Empty file is only here to create a plugin.
```

#### `enumProvidingProj/src/main/java/SomeEnum.java`

```lang-java
public enum SomeEnum {
    FOO, BAR, BAZ;
}
```

#### `enumUsingProj/build.gradle`

```lang-groovy
plugins {
  id &#39;java&#39;
  id &#39;my-enum-convention&#39;
}

import SomeEnum

task someTask() {
    def foo = SomeEnum.FOO
    doLast() {
        println(&quot;$foo&quot;)
    }
}

someTask.dependsOn compileJava
```

#### `enumUsingProj/settings.gradle`

```lang-groovy
pluginManagement {
    includeBuild &#39;../enumProvidingProj&#39;
}
```

